title: fix NCHWc intermediates as graph outputs
body:
**Description**: This fixes a customer reported issue where the NCHWc optimizer was dropping graph outputs when an edge was used as both a graph output and an input to another NCHWc node.

**Motivation and Context**
This fixes the problem reported in #3029 . The test model uses each intermediate tensor in the graph as input to the next NCHWc node and also includes the tensor in graph's outputs. The optimizer was not counting the graph output use in this case, so the Finalize pass did not emit ReorderOutput nodes to maintain the link to the graph outputs.

Added a test case for this type of graph. Also verified that the customer model runs as expected.

title: NCHWc ReorderOutput->Transpose(NHWC) fusion
body:
**Description**: Add support to fuse ReorderOutput+Transpose(NHWC). Converting from NCHWc to NHWC tensors is a trivial copy of data and avoids the cost of a transpose node.

**Motivation and Context**
Many models are converted from NHWC sources and while the model converter can optimize away most transposes, not all can be easily removed. This adds support for one part of the problem: instead of reordering NCHWc to NCHW and then doing a transpose to NHWC, extend the ReorderOutput op to support NHWC directly.

The other part of the problem, converting NHWC to NCHWc via ReorderInput nodes, will be handled later.

As an example, tinyyolov3 from the model zoo goes from 22.7ms->22.4ms per inference.

title: Eliminate redundant subexpressions
body:
**Description**: Apply local value numbering to merge graph nodes that will always
evaluate to the same value.

**Motivation and Context**
When a model is exported from a high-level framework, and the original source code reuses some functions, these functions may create multiple graph portions that compute the same expression. This change eliminates redundant computation.

As an alternative, this optimization could be applied on case-by-case basis in the original source code (e.g. PyTorch). However, existence of redundant computation may be non-obvious; also, if part of the source code is third-party, it complicates things even more.

This implementation is quite basic and could be improved in future. For example, we could merge identical constant initializers or apply global value numbering (working across subgraphs).

title: Properly handle downlevel and WCOS scenarios
body:
**Description**: 
1) Add a switch, enable_wcos, that will toggle whether ORT links against windowsapp.lib and avoids default libs like kernel32.lib.
2) Eliminate dependency of winml_adapter on cppwinrt.
3) Various fixes to get winml api and scenario tests to pass down-level to win 8.1

**Motivation and Context**
When WinML merged into ORT we already started linking onnxruntime against windowsapp.lib because CMAKE_C_STANDARD_LIBRARIES and CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD_LIBRARIES were being set which has global effects. This PR ensures again that onnxruntime won't link against windowsapp.lib unless the wcos scenario is specifically requested. All our pipelines for now will continue not enabling wcos. The work to remove winrt from winml_adapter was necessary to get onnxruntime to build with the adapter but without linking against windowsapp.lib.

title: Create a separate Nuget hosting just managed assemblies
body:
This change has 2 parts -

Remove the coupling between the OnnxRuntime managed assembly and specific EPs. The managed ORT managed dll is now common across all EPs.

Separate out the managed OnnxRuntime assembly into a separate Nuget (Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Managed). The EP-specific native shared library artifacts will be part of separate EP-specific nugets (eg: Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime for CPU and Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime .Gpu for GPU). The "native" nuget will depend on the "managed" nuget so as to bring it into relevant projects automatically.

Resolve #2184

title: NCHWc Upsample/Mul optimizations
body:
**Description**: Extend the NCHWc layout optimizer to handle Resize(mode=nearest) and Mul.

**Motivation and Context**
Add support for trivial Upsample and Resize ops using nearest mode upsampling with integer scaling in the NCHWc domain. This is meant to handle UNet and YOLOV3 models that have an UpsampleNearest(2x2) node. This avoids unnecessary tensor reordering around the upsampling.

Also reuse the existing Add/Sum support to keep tensors in NCHWc when both inputs of a Mul node are already in NCHWc format.

One internal model using Upsample and Mul went from 27ms->21ms per inference. tinyyolov3 from the model zoo went from 16ms->14ms.

title: Fix WCOS/Win32 linking bugs
body:
Edit: Scope of this PR has changed. After some discussion it seems like ORT will build for WCOS after version 1.2. I'm removing the WCOS/Win32 hacks and using the CMake cross-compilation options to target WCOS or Win32. When using the VS generator, this also sets the project type in VS, so it's easy to see in the project pane if you're targeting Win32 or Store.

 ----

**Description**: WCOS/Win32 linking options were error prone, because CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD_LIBRARIES was left at the default value (which includes Win32 libs). The WCOS targets were being linked with both Win32 and WCOS libs, which links with the wrong library if you swap the order of the libraries (e.g. refactoring), and can lead to subtle bugs by accidentally calling a Win32 function and linking to a Win32 library.

title: Thread pool changes
body:
**Description**: 
1. Copy tensorflow's thread pool class to ORT, so that we can get a better implementation of thread pool based parallelfor
2. Copy Eigen's thread pool class to ORT
3. Support thread affinity
4. Remove RNN kernels private thread pool
5. Modify pool kernels to use the thread pool when openmp is disabled.

Extra notes:

When you parallel a for loop, the number of the thread pool tasks to schedule should be based on complexity of the problem(cost of each iteration).  You have to run benchmarks to get a good understanding of the problem. 

Thread affinity doesn't help much in most of the settings. Usually the performance difference is less than 2% and hard to measure. 

For the changes in Maxpool kernel, if mlas is disabled, and thread pool is in use,  we can see linear speed up on my local dev machine which has 4 cores. So the threading changes itself is good, but, ORT's own max pool implementation is about 10x slower than mlas. So it has a large room to improve. 


**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Use GEMM for LinearRegressor and LinearClassifier operators to improve performance
body:
**Description**: 
Use GEMM for LinearRegressor.
Update scores in-place with any post processor to avoid unnecessary allocations/copies.

**Motivation and Context**
Improve performance of SKL benchmarks.

**Validation**
Took 2 models generated from the skl2onnx unit tests that used LinearRegressor. One had 2 targets, the other had 1. Created inputs with batch sizes of 100, 500 and 2500. Ran each model for 30,000 iterations with onnxruntime_perf_test.exe using v1.1.2 vs. latest master with these changes.

Also tried to use the threadpool for the softmax calculations, but there wasn't a clear benefit to doing so. Would be better to switch to using the implementation in the Softmax operator instead if that turns out to be a performance issue.

Batch size | Version | SklearnLinearRegression-Dec4 | 2 targets

 | new | Average inference time cost | 0.00690207

 | new | Average inference time cost | 0.00898752 
 |  | Speedup | 14.60 
 |  |  |

title: Support custom ops targeting the CUDA EP
body:
Currently, the CUDA GetCapability() method ignores all other (custom) kernel registries apart from the CUDA kernel registry when trying to assign a node to the CUDA EP. This prevents users of the custom op API to target the CUDA EP. 

Resolve https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3138

title: update C# API to optimize inference latency
body:
**Description**: This change update ONNXRuntime C# API to support more override of `InferenceSession.Run()`.

**Features**:
- Support pre-allocated outputs with determined types and dimensions.
- Support a new type `PinnedOnnxValue` to allow user to reuse the underlying native `OrtValue` for multiple times.
- Added overrides of the combination of above with no break of any existing interface.

**Motivation and Context**
- ONNXRuntime C# does not have a good inference performance with small models under a multi-thread situation. The main reason is that the current C# API always allocate buffers for outputs and create native `OrtValue` objects in `InferenceSession.Run()`. However, this can be avoid by calling C-API with a pre-allocated output list and use a pinned memory, as discussed in the design review meeting.

title: Performance improvement to Transpose when moving single axis.
body:
**Description**: 
Avoid use of vectors for tracking reader/writer offsets as it adds too much overhead if there are a lot of readers or writers. 

**Motivation and Context**
Tracy found improvements in resnet34-ssd1200 and BERT Squad with this approach.

title: Introduce ORT Training Implementation [DO NOT MERGE]
body:
Summary of changes to ORT

Framework:
- Support Tensor with byte_offset
- Introduce a mode for partial graph execution: only_execute_path_to_fetches
- Fine grain control on Graph.Resolve(), it needs a new mode for mixed_precision graph type inference
- Richer Graph API for modifying the training graph
- Enable setting CUDA memory limit at EP construction time
- SessionState supports getting/modifying initializer tensor values
- Memory for Initializer and activation tensors are allocated differently
- Introduced node-level profiler to SequentialExecutor (can be optional turn on)

Platform:
- Introduced utility functions for Create/Delete/CheckIfExist folder

Optimizer
- LayerNorm Fusion will add two additional outputs
- Constant folding is currently disabled (need to introduce a switch)
- Removed BiasGelu Fusion (need to fix this)
- Introduced MatmulTransposeFusion

External package:
- cxxopt (command line option parser)
- horovod (for distributed training)
- tensorboard
